To solve the system of equations

\[
\begin{align*}
4k + q + 3 &= 0, \quad \text{(Equation 1)} \\
2k + k - q + 4 &= 0, \quad \text{(Equation 2)}
\end{align*}
\]

we can use either the substitution method or the elimination method. Here, I'll use the elimination method to eliminate one variable from each equation, leaving me with just one equation to solve for \( k \).

### Step 1: Eliminate \( q \) from both equations

To eliminate \( q \), we can multiply Equation 1 by \( k \) and Equation 2 by \( -k \). This will make the coefficients of \( q \) in both equations cancel each other out.

\[
\begin{align*}
4k^2 + k + 3k &= 0, \quad \text{(Multiplying Equation 1 by \( k \))} \\
2k^2 - k - 4k &= 0, \quad \text{(Multiplying Equation 2 by \( -k \))}
\end{align*}
\]

Let's perform this multiplication.

